able to travel on this lake and

03:05.319 --> 03:06.451
I won't be able to fish.

03:06.453 --> 03:08.053
That's why I wanna
focus on, on, big game,

03:08.121 --> 03:10.055
'cause that's what's gonna
get me through the winter.

03:10.123 --> 03:12.858
That's pretty much all I
need for several months,

03:12.926 --> 03:17.262
so this location here is
gonna be a great starting point.

03:17.331 --> 03:21.200
Each morning that I can just
wake up in a little shelter and

03:21.268 --> 03:22.434
just hit the ground runnin'.

03:24.405 --> 03:26.004
What do you think, Javs?

03:26.006 --> 03:28.073
You wanna call this
home for a little bit?

03:28.075 --> 03:32.077
Couple little trials with
the ice but Java's having fun.

03:32.145 --> 03:33.879
Beautiful beach.

03:33.947 --> 03:35.547
What more could I ask for?

03:35.882 --> 03:38.150
Yeah, these trees...

03:38.218 --> 03:43.488
I'm kinda just looking for two trees
that are about my body length apart,

03:43.490 --> 03:45.157
something I can lay between.

03:45.225 --> 03:47.559
Nothing fancy, but something's
that's just gonna allow me to

03:47.628 --> 03:49.127
just wake up and go hunting.

03:51.031 --> 03:52.430
I think these
are gonna work good.

03:53.300 --> 03:55.000
So, clock's ticking,
it's time to get to work.

03:57.504 --> 04:00.171
SONTA: Indigenous people,
are the first scientists,

04:00.174 --> 04:01.240
of our world.

04:01.308 --> 04:04.309
We're so connected to
what the animals are doing,

04:04.378 --> 04:06.912
what the fish are doing and
they haven't returned this year.

04:06.980 --> 04:08.446
The cycles have changed.

04:08.449 --> 04:10.315
That's really
scary in the Arctic.

