our net sometimes we get filled

16:32.676 --> 16:34.275
with a bunch of drift.

16:34.344 --> 16:36.744
You can't catch fish if
you're catching sticks.

16:36.813 --> 16:38.346
Little problematic.

16:38.348 --> 16:41.949
So the fishing is, uh,
been down this year,

16:42.018 --> 16:44.151
there hasn't
been any summer chum,

16:44.154 --> 16:47.488
haven't been able to
target any salmon so, uh,

16:47.490 --> 16:48.690
another little bump in the road,

16:48.758 --> 16:51.225
gotta keep rolling
through it though man.

16:51.294 --> 16:52.760
Can't sweat the small stuff.

16:52.829 --> 16:54.495
We're gonna catch
fish sooner or later,

16:54.564 --> 16:57.165
you just gotta stick to it
so that's what we're gonna do.

17:00.170 --> 17:02.570
All right, I'm gonna
pull up here to the net, um.

17:02.638 --> 17:05.239
I'm not seeing tons of drift
right here floating towards

17:05.308 --> 17:08.242
the net so that's a
good thing, but, uh,

17:08.244 --> 17:10.978
we do have some drift in there.

17:10.980 --> 17:14.582
But I just hope for no big logs
or anything that gets rolled up

17:14.650 --> 17:17.985
in there something where
I gotta, it rips my net or

17:17.987 --> 17:23.257
does something funky
like that, so, uh, see here.

17:26.062 --> 17:28.329
Yeah, that's a
lot of drift in here.

17:28.398 --> 17:30.531
(bleep).

17:30.533 --> 17:31.899
Just gotta deal with it.

17:33.803 --> 17:35.136
Oh look at that.

17:40.260 --> 17:42.860
♪ ♪

17:42.862 --> 17:44.662
CHEVIE: Oh look at that.

17:44.730 --> 17:47.731
We even caught a...

17:47.734 --> 17:49.533
Could be a score.

17:49.536 --> 17:52.403
Look at that
factory two by eight.

17:52.472 --> 17:53.104
(laughs)

17:55.875 --> 17:57.475
Don't find that every day.

17:57.543 --> 17:59.610
Well, this is gonna
be a little bit of work,

17:59.679 --> 18:05.083
glad the kids aren't here
wondering what's going on, uh...

18:05.151 --> 18:08.736
We'll try to get this cleared
up without ripping my net,

18:08.788 --> 18:11.222
that's the big thing so
that I can get this reset.

18:11.224 --> 18:15.359
When you get
high water, wind, rain,

18:15.428 --> 18:17.428
all at the same time
and you're catching,

18:17.430 --> 18:19.763
there's this much
drift you can't fish it,

18:19.766 --> 18:21.899
it's just too,
it's just too dirty.

18:21.968 --> 18:24.702
So I need to get this out
of here sooner than later.

18:24.704 --> 18:28.172
I'm gonna get my net cleaned up,
we'll get this net set again and

18:28.174 --> 18:29.573
we'll keep on fishing.

18:29.576 --> 18:32.877
Today wasn't our day but
we'll, uh, that day will come.

18:35.515 --> 18:37.648
ROBERT: My son RJ is a student.

18:37.717 --> 18:39.517
He's a student of the hunting.

18:39.585 --> 18:40.784
(gunshot)

18:40.787 --> 18:42.386
He's a student of the fishing.

18:42.722 --> 18:45.389
He's been a student of his dad.

18:45.391 --> 18:47.792
My son's following
in my footsteps and

18:47.860 --> 18:50.061
it's just been
so amazing to see.

18:53.533 --> 18:55.132
ROBERT: I'm pretty
excited to get some halibut,

18:55.135 --> 18:58.002
that's one of my
favorite things to fish.

18:58.070 --> 18:59.603
I love catching halibut.

18:59.606 --> 19:01.139
There's a lot of
sharks out here, too.

19:01.207 --> 19:02.607
I hope we can get through 'em.

19:02.675 --> 19:03.841
RJ: Oh, I'm
sure it will be fine.

19:05.278 --> 19:06.944
ROBERT: So we just got
our limit of sea bass in,

19:06.946 --> 19:08.613
we're on our way out to
the halibut spot now.

19:08.681 --> 19:10.748
The water looks great
today for halibut fishing,

19:10.750 --> 19:12.416
so that's gonna
be our main goal.

19:12.418 --> 19:13.818
We'll go out there and
we're gonna throw the hook,

19:13.886 --> 19:15.953
anchor up and we're gonna
try to catch some halibut.

19:17.890 --> 19:19.557
Can you put a
three pounder on ours?

19:19.625 --> 19:21.292
RJ: Yup.

19:22.962 --> 19:25.163
ROBERT: So we're out here now,
we got the anchor set, um.

19:25.231 --> 19:27.165
We put a three pound weight on

19:27.233 --> 19:29.833
and a hook and
then we have a bait bin here

19:29.836 --> 19:31.502
that's full of salmon carcasses

19:31.571 --> 19:35.106
and we're just gonna put remnants
of the salmon on our hooks.

19:35.174 --> 19:36.707
We'll, uh, drop
them to the bottom,

19:36.709 --> 19:38.860
trying to get a chum trail.

19:38.912 --> 19:41.179
We'll be putting a lot
of fresh bait down here.

19:41.247 --> 19:43.314
Trying to get that scent
trail going out with the tide,

19:43.316 --> 19:44.848
and that will attract them in.

19:44.851 --> 19:48.186
It's like bears coming in to
a fresh kill on the beach so

19:48.254 --> 19:49.720
they can smell
it from miles away.

19:54.928 --> 19:56.827
Fishing now.

20:00.600 --> 20:01.899
See what happens.

20:04.204 --> 20:05.736
RJ: Fish on!

20:05.738 --> 20:06.637
ROBERT: That looked
like a good bite, RJ.

20:06.656 --> 20:09.407
Is it on?

20:09.475 --> 20:10.875
RJ: Oh, it's on.

20:10.943 --> 20:11.943
You wanna get up that one, Dad?

20:12.011 --> 20:13.277
ROBERT: Yeah, bud.

20:14.080 --> 20:16.214
Halibut, five minutes,
one halibut.

20:16.282 --> 20:18.950
RJ: That's like a 30 incher.
ROBERT: Those are good eaters.

20:21.020 --> 20:23.287
There you go.

20:23.356 --> 20:25.022
Nice, this is a good one.

20:25.024 --> 20:26.490
Bleed him, throw him in the box.

20:31.030 --> 20:32.763
RJ: Yeah let me
get my line down.

20:33.099 --> 20:36.834
ROBERT: With chum trail it's
very similar to a hyena and

20:36.836 --> 20:40.037
there's a dead animal, and
it starts to stink pretty bad.

20:40.106 --> 20:44.508
I imagine every hyena within
five miles down wind of that is

20:44.577 --> 20:45.710
gonna come in and investigate.

20:45.778 --> 20:47.378
Well, halibut are the same way.

20:47.380 --> 20:49.313
They're gonna come investigate
because they're always hungry

20:49.315 --> 20:50.648
and they wanna eat, too.

20:50.716 --> 20:52.016
RJ: There we go, ready, Dad?

20:54.453 --> 20:57.188
ROBERT: Sometimes it takes an
hour or two to the chum these halibut in,

20:57.256 --> 21:00.124
and sometimes you just get
lucky and catch 'em right away.

21:03.663 --> 21:05.062
I got a little one on, chicken.

21:08.334 --> 21:09.967
There it is.

21:12.138 --> 21:14.372
I got my limit, I'm gonna eat
that one for dinner tonight.

21:16.676 --> 21:18.475
That will be a good
family meal right there.

21:18.678 --> 21:21.345
Well, we limited it out
on halibut and, and sea bass.

21:21.414 --> 21:22.613
RJ: Yup.

21:22.615 --> 21:23.614
ROBERT: That wasn't too hard,

21:23.683 --> 21:25.883
but today I had a
lot of fun with you RJ.

21:25.951 --> 21:28.819
RJ: Good, I had
fun with you, too.

21:28.888 --> 21:32.023
ROBERT: All right, pull this
anchor and get out of here.

21:32.091 --> 21:33.824
Maybe tomorrow
we'll get a bigger one.

21:37.763 --> 21:39.363
SONTA: Fishing is one of the
things that we want to make sure

21:39.432 --> 21:43.634
our kids know about,
care about, yearn for.

21:43.636 --> 21:46.237
It's our livelihood, it's
something we really enjoy and

21:46.305 --> 21:49.173
it's something that we want to instill
in the kids as a really strong value.

21:49.241 --> 21:50.341
Part of who they are.

21:56.582 --> 21:57.381
SONTA: Ah, this feels nice.

21:57.450 --> 21:58.849
Pretty warm out
right now, I like that.

21:58.918 --> 22:00.384
CHEVIE: It is, it is nice out.

22:00.386 --> 22:03.054
SONTA: Compared
to the rainy cold,

22:03.122 --> 22:05.323
I mean this is foggy
but it's pretty warm out.

22:05.391 --> 22:06.991
CHEVIE: 50 degrees.

22:07.059 --> 22:09.193
Just another day on the Innoko,

22:09.261 --> 22:12.062
we're just happy to be on
the river right now and, uh,

22:12.065 --> 22:14.131
be able to check the net.

22:14.467 --> 22:16.600
So I'm really, really
looking forward to it.

22:16.602 --> 22:18.269
What are we gonna
get in our net today, kids?

22:18.337 --> 22:21.205
EMERY: Whitefish!
RYDER: Pike.

22:21.207 --> 22:23.407
EMERY: Whitefish,
whitefish, whitefish, whitefish.

22:23.476 --> 22:24.675
Whitefish!

22:24.677 --> 22:27.278
CHEVIE: You know what I'm always
hoping for is no driftwood.

22:27.346 --> 22:28.679
SONTA: There we go.

22:28.748 --> 22:30.681
So every day's a
different day out on the water.

22:30.750 --> 22:33.484
You know, one day we get
all driftwood in the net.

22:33.552 --> 22:35.953
Some days they're just a bust,
that's one of the things that

22:36.021 --> 22:37.421
comes with just fishing.

22:37.490 --> 22:39.890
So we hope for fish every day,
we weren't able to get that

22:39.959 --> 22:44.028
many this summer so we're
setting our, our net in the water,

22:44.096 --> 22:46.830
checking it every day and
slowly over time we're gonna

22:46.833 --> 22:48.766
increase the number
of fish that we catch.

22:48.834 --> 22:50.834
Increase the number of fish
we have in our freezer which is

22:50.837 --> 22:53.204
none right now and just
put it away for the winter.

22:58.444 --> 23:00.911
Okay, let's see
what's in this net, guys.

23:00.980 --> 23:02.179
Sydney you're gonna help me?

23:02.181 --> 23:03.481
SYDNEY: Uh, yeah.

23:06.719 --> 23:09.119
SONTA: Let's see
what's in this net.

23:09.122 --> 23:10.588
Come on, Bean.

23:13.793 --> 23:16.594
Hopefully we got more
fish than we do drift,

23:16.662 --> 23:18.396
it looks like we got
some drift in the net.

23:20.199 --> 23:21.331
SYDNEY: I thought that
was a fish or something.

23:21.334 --> 23:22.800
SONTA: Okay.

23:22.868 --> 23:25.068
Yeah, so this is definitely not
fish and definitely not alligators but

23:25.071 --> 23:26.870
we got some major
drift in the net.

23:27.073 --> 23:28.606
Oh, what do we got here Chev?

23:28.674 --> 23:30.040
SYDNEY: What is that?

23:35.498 --> 23:37.698
'S in this net.

23:37.767 --> 23:39.767
Oh, what have we got here, Chev?

23:39.769 --> 23:42.903
SYDNEY: What is that?
SONTA: Oh, there we go.

23:42.972 --> 23:44.304
What kind of fish is that?

23:44.307 --> 23:45.639
SYDNEY: Look, it's a pike.
SONTA: There you go.

23:45.641 --> 23:47.575
Pull that pike in.

23:47.643 --> 23:49.643
Good job.

23:52.315 --> 23:53.781
Keep pulling it.

23:53.849 --> 23:55.783
There's only one way to teach
and that's getting your hands

23:55.851 --> 23:57.852
in there and getting busy.

23:57.920 --> 24:00.587
Pull it hard.

24:00.590 --> 24:02.857
And then you
start wiggling it out.

24:04.326 --> 24:06.193
Nice.

24:07.330 --> 24:09.263
It's been great just
to watch Sydney learn.

24:09.265 --> 24:11.598
She was out there getting
her hands in the water,

24:11.601 --> 24:13.400
getting her
hands on the fishnet,

24:13.469 --> 24:14.935
getting more aware
of her surroundings,

24:15.004 --> 24:16.303
and kinda what's going on.

24:18.541 --> 24:20.140
SYDNEY: I think we should be
careful with that fish, Mom.

24:20.143 --> 24:22.743
I see that the net's
not fully around it.

24:22.745 --> 24:23.544
SONTA: That's okay.

24:23.612 --> 24:24.812
It's probably
caught in the gills.

24:24.814 --> 24:26.280
This is really
called a gill net.

24:26.282 --> 24:29.416
It's 'cause it gets
caught in the gills.

24:29.485 --> 24:31.018
SYDNEY: True.

24:31.020 --> 24:32.286
Is that whitefish, Mom?

24:32.288 --> 24:33.487
CHEVIE: Yeah,
that's a whitefish.

24:33.556 --> 24:35.022
SONTA: Whitefish.
SYDNEY: Yes! I was right!

24:35.090 --> 24:36.824
SONTA: Hold on,
I'm stuck, there we go.

24:37.960 --> 24:39.093
It's coming in, Emery.

24:39.161 --> 24:41.962
We got your whitefish for
you, hanging on by a gill.

24:42.031 --> 24:45.032
After you get really good at
this, Sydney, you'll be fast.

24:45.100 --> 24:46.366
Here you go, babe.

24:46.369 --> 24:47.701
There's your whitefish, Emery.

24:47.703 --> 24:50.103
Yahoo! Still alive.

24:50.106 --> 24:52.506
Nice and fresh,
this is exciting.

24:52.508 --> 24:54.041
It's a good spot.

24:54.043 --> 24:56.510
We could be here all day,
just back and forth.

24:56.512 --> 24:57.311
Checking this net.

24:57.313 --> 24:58.712
(laughs)

25:00.850 --> 25:02.116
I think there's a
lot of people that think

25:02.184 --> 25:04.718
they can do this kind of work.

25:04.720 --> 25:08.255
And it just takes being on
site and learning how to do it.

25:08.257 --> 25:09.523
And so that's
really how we teach.

25:09.592 --> 25:10.791
And Sydney's doing great.

25:10.860 --> 25:12.159
We're really proud of her.

25:14.197 --> 25:15.796
There you go.

25:15.865 --> 25:18.065
Okay, it'll start to
straighten itself out here.

25:18.067 --> 25:19.399
Good job.

25:19.402 --> 25:21.735
All right Sydney, so we
got about what, four fish?

25:21.737 --> 25:23.003
SYDNEY: Um, yeah.

25:23.005 --> 25:25.873
SONTA: Four fish is, um, kind
of what we expected actually.

25:25.875 --> 25:27.608
Um, this is starvation time.

25:27.676 --> 25:30.143
Things are hard right now and
so we're happy with what we got.

25:30.146 --> 25:32.946
We'll get these in the smokehouse
and get hung and start drying.

25:32.949 --> 25:34.081
Cool.

25:34.149 --> 25:35.415
Okay, Chev, we're good.

25:35.418 --> 25:38.485
Good job, all in
a day's work, kids.

25:38.487 --> 25:40.287
Let's get this fish cut up.

25:44.493 --> 25:48.028
JOHNNY: Subsistence hunter,
gatherer, fisherman, butcher,

25:48.030 --> 25:51.632
chef, logger, craftsman.

25:51.700 --> 25:54.902
All these different
jobs in order to thrive

25:54.970 --> 25:56.703
and subsist out
here in the wild.

25:57.306 --> 26:02.709
No other job I've ever had requires
me to have that many job titles.

26:02.712 --> 26:04.211
And I think it's pretty cool.

26:05.448 --> 26:11.819
(imitating moose calls)

26:18.727 --> 26:21.996
JONHHY: Yeah, I wake up today
so ambitious to get out hunting.

26:22.064 --> 26:24.331
And what I wanna
target is moose.

26:24.333 --> 26:26.267
But the first
thing about hunting,

26:26.335 --> 26:31.605
my game plan is generally to
just let the land speak to me.

26:31.607 --> 26:34.474
Let the land tell me
what I should be hunting.

26:34.477 --> 26:35.776
You're doing good, Java.

26:38.614 --> 26:40.781
The wind's blowing this
way which is excellent.

26:42.885 --> 26:47.287
'Cause, 'cause it keeps my scent away
from where I think the moose would be.

26:47.290 --> 26:48.622
There's a little
tundra behind, like,

26:48.691 --> 26:51.158
right over there.

26:51.160 --> 26:53.627
And I think moose
would be hanging out there.

26:53.696 --> 26:55.696
I just gotta listen
and I got to stay quiet.

26:55.698 --> 26:57.698
So it's kinda
finding the balance,

26:57.766 --> 27:00.167
trying to figure out,
what do I wanna hunt?

27:00.169 --> 27:03.103
Because if I go out
there with a closed mind,

27:03.105 --> 27:05.439
thinking this is
what I want from nature,

27:05.441 --> 27:07.174
nature won't give it to me.

27:07.242 --> 27:09.309
Nature's gonna
tell me what to hunt.

27:09.312 --> 27:12.179
Nature's gonna tell me
what animal to go after,

27:12.247 --> 27:15.382
and I'm going to listen to
nature as I always do 'cause

27:15.451 --> 27:16.917
nature's never steered me wrong.

27:20.122 --> 27:22.456
I think I see caribou swimming
across the lake right now.

27:25.995 --> 27:31.531
See, that's the problem with
calling for moose in caribou country,

27:31.534 --> 27:33.800
is that they're
going north right now.

27:33.803 --> 27:36.070
But this time
of year, caribou go south.

27:36.138 --> 27:38.138
So, that means they
came across the lake,

27:38.207 --> 27:40.808
probably heard me
calling for moose,

27:40.876 --> 27:43.944
and they bailed 'cause
they're swimming fast.

27:44.013 --> 27:45.746
They wouldn't be swimming
fast for fun, you know?

27:45.814 --> 27:47.681
They're swimming
fast to get away,

27:47.750 --> 27:49.549
because they probably heard me.

27:49.552 --> 27:50.851
(bleep).

27:52.955 --> 27:57.624
It feels like I just blew my caribou
chances by focusing on moose.

27:57.693 --> 27:59.359
That's a bummer.

27:59.362 --> 28:03.563
I think I'm gonna see
if they go left or right.

28:03.566 --> 28:07.634
If they go left, they're
gonna go along the lake.

28:07.703 --> 28:09.870
And I'm gonna head
this way and intercept 'em.

28:12.441 --> 28:14.241
Yeah, I got one going
this way right now.

28:14.243 --> 28:15.709
Let's boogie.

28:17.780 --> 28:19.446
Java, come on.

28:19.515 --> 28:21.215
Let's go. Come on.

28:25.521 --> 28:27.387
Caribou are
incredible swimmers and that,

28:27.390 --> 28:29.923
that lake's over a mile wide.

28:29.925 --> 28:31.959
They're just swimming
across it like it's nothing.

28:34.063 --> 28:38.331
Seeing caribou scared and swimming
across the lake isn't a problem.

28:38.334 --> 28:40.267
To me, it's a solution.

28:40.269 --> 28:44.204
It's finding answers
by listening to the land,

28:44.273 --> 28:46.940
by paying attention to nature.

28:46.942 --> 28:49.476
It's telling me,
abandon the moose hunt.

28:49.545 --> 28:51.111
Go for caribou.

28:57.419 --> 28:59.019
ROBERT: My family
has been in Sitka, Alaska,

28:59.088 --> 29:00.620
for 10,000 years.

29:00.623 --> 29:04.992
It's in my blood and I think there's
generational muscle-memory that's passed on.

29:06.895 --> 29:10.297
I was able to pick it up and
continue with modern technology,

29:10.299 --> 29:11.398
and I think that's awesome.

29:17.773 --> 29:19.306
Today we're out here,
we're gonna head out and

29:19.308 --> 29:20.641
try and get some halibut.

29:20.709 --> 29:24.111
Fill up my freezer and try to
feed some elders at the same time.

29:24.113 --> 29:25.179
It's gonna be a great day.

29:30.519 --> 29:32.385
We're gonna anchor up here
for at least a couple hours.

29:32.388 --> 29:34.521
See if we can catch a
halibut to take home.

29:35.791 --> 29:37.858
Just waiting for the boat to
settle down a little bit here.

29:39.328 --> 29:41.462
I think I brought RJ
fishing when he was, uh,

29:41.530 --> 29:43.864
probably less than
six months old with me.

29:45.668 --> 29:47.601
He's been coming ever since.

29:47.603 --> 29:50.337
He knows his stuff
out here really well.

29:50.339 --> 29:53.474
I couldn't imagine having a
better fishing buddy than my son.

29:53.542 --> 29:55.342
It seems like every time
I pick up the phone to say,

29:55.410 --> 29:56.610
"Hey, you wanna go fishing?"

29:56.678 --> 29:59.413
For some reason my son's
number is on speed-dial and

29:59.481 --> 30:01.348
that's the only person I call.

30:01.350 --> 30:03.083
Three-pound lead today.

30:03.152 --> 30:04.618
Let's see if we can
get down there with that.

30:06.622 --> 30:08.088
All right, going down.

30:08.157 --> 30:09.156
I'm excited.

30:09.224 --> 30:11.158
Going fishing.

30:12.027 --> 30:13.694
We're going after
the big boys today.

30:14.763 --> 30:16.497
Get it to go through all,
through all the sharks.

30:16.565 --> 30:18.899
It's at about 90 feet right now.

30:24.707 --> 30:26.907
Fish on! We got a ripper.

30:26.975 --> 30:30.711
RJ: There he goes.
ROBERT: Big one over here.

30:30.779 --> 30:32.112
It's still
taking line, look at that.

30:32.181 --> 30:33.147
RJ: Hell, yeah.

30:35.984 --> 30:37.050
(grunts)

30:37.386 --> 30:39.786
ROBERT: We got a shark.

30:39.788 --> 30:41.522
Them things are strong.

30:45.728 --> 30:47.127
(bleep)!

30:47.196 --> 30:48.862
I am having the hardest time.

30:48.864 --> 30:50.597
RJ: Here I'll, uh,
help you out with that.

30:50.599 --> 30:52.966
ROBERT: I can see the hook.
It'll be an easy release.

30:55.337 --> 30:56.503
Watch your hand.

30:58.407 --> 30:59.706
Good job.

31:00.876 --> 31:02.809
What do you think
that was, a 40-pound shark?

31:02.811 --> 31:05.646
RJ: I don't know.
Two and a half feet?

31:08.350 --> 31:09.983
ROBERT: That oughta
do something.

31:15.558 --> 31:17.658
Come on fish.
I know you're down there.

31:18.760 --> 31:20.027
RJ: Holy cow!

31:20.095 --> 31:21.562
(laughs)

31:21.630 --> 31:22.896
ROBERT: Are you on?

31:22.965 --> 31:25.799
RJ: Yeah, I'm on.
ROBERT: We're fishing now.

31:27.436 --> 31:29.303
Got a big one on.
At least 100 pounds.

31:29.638 --> 31:31.838
RJ: I can't even
get him off the bottom.

31:31.907 --> 31:33.240
ROBERT: Oh, you're
gaining on it now.

31:33.242 --> 31:34.741
A little bit.

31:37.179 --> 31:39.646
Oh, there it is, color.

31:39.648 --> 31:41.381
What is it?

31:41.450 --> 31:42.516
RJ: This thing is a monster.

31:48.574 --> 31:50.240
♪ ♪

31:50.242 --> 31:52.375
ROBERT: What is it?
RJ: This thing is a monster.

31:52.378 --> 31:58.382
I think it's a big
freaking huge halibut.

31:59.919 --> 32:03.320
ROBERT: Oh, my God.

32:03.322 --> 32:05.121
Maybe 160 pounder.

32:05.124 --> 32:06.990
RJ: Yeah, 160, 150.

32:06.992 --> 32:09.192
ROBERT: There's gonna be a lot
of food there for the freezer.

32:09.261 --> 32:11.528
RJ: Definitely.
That's a good sized keeper.

32:11.596 --> 32:13.664
If I can, oh, he's peeling now.

32:13.732 --> 32:16.767
ROBERT: Good job, RJ.
RJ: Well, we're not there yet.

32:18.003 --> 32:19.937
They come off just as easy.

32:20.005 --> 32:21.538
You wanna grab it
over on this side?

32:21.540 --> 32:23.206
Nah.

32:23.275 --> 32:24.674
ROBERT: Just
hold him here, right?

32:24.677 --> 32:26.510
RJ: Yeah, just keep
his head under the water.

32:27.680 --> 32:29.513
Make sure he's got hooks in.

32:33.686 --> 32:35.618
ROBERT: We didn't get the
other one on the other side, RJ.

32:35.621 --> 32:37.554
That was, that gap
straightens out on you.

32:53.438 --> 32:55.238
RJ: Woo! Nice!
ROBERT: Yeah.

32:55.240 --> 32:57.908
RJ: That's a nice 'but.
ROBERT: Hey, girl.

32:57.976 --> 32:59.242
What do you think?

32:59.244 --> 33:01.044
That thing can kick your
butt if you're not careful.

33:01.046 --> 33:03.380
RJ: Yeah, that's probably...
ROBERT: 130?

33:03.382 --> 33:06.649
RJ: If I take a good guess, he's
probably about 57, 58 inches and

33:06.652 --> 33:09.119
I'm gonna say probably 120, 130.

33:09.187 --> 33:10.854
ROBERT: 130?
Yeah, that's about right.

33:10.856 --> 33:12.055
RJ: I think you and
I will both be set,

33:12.057 --> 33:13.924
as well as a few
old ladies in town.

33:13.992 --> 33:16.059
ROBERT: Let's go home, bud.
RJ: Sounds good.

33:16.128 --> 33:18.128
Let's call it a day. Nice work.

33:18.196 --> 33:19.729
ROBERT: Good job, bud.

33:19.732 --> 33:21.197
It was a good day.

33:21.200 --> 33:22.399
Awesome.

33:27.806 --> 33:29.539
CHEVIE: Every year's
a new year with kids.

33:29.541 --> 33:33.009
Stuff that you taught 'em last year
is just a stepping stone for this year.

33:33.012 --> 33:35.345
The learning here
takes place on the land.

33:35.347 --> 33:37.013
And that's where we're gonna be,

33:37.016 --> 33:38.315
and that's where
our kids are gonna be.

33:41.153 --> 33:42.819
CHEVIE: All right, Ry-Ry, we're
gonna look for cottonwood

33:42.888 --> 33:45.022
for the smoke house.

33:45.090 --> 33:48.024
It's kinda fun to do stuff
with just me and you, huh?

33:48.027 --> 33:49.626
Yeah.

33:49.628 --> 33:51.961
Hey, look at that cottonwood
right over there, Ryder.

33:51.964 --> 33:53.363
That, that one
looks pretty good.

33:53.365 --> 33:56.500
That's a, its
leaves dead at the top.

33:57.836 --> 34:00.637
There's our, there's our
cottonwood right there, Ryder.

34:00.639 --> 34:04.241
And look it, we got this nice
little place to tie our boat up here.

34:04.309 --> 34:06.410
Let's go up
there and have a look.

34:12.985 --> 34:14.717
You're gonna have
to grab that one.

34:14.720 --> 34:15.852
That one over there.

34:15.854 --> 34:17.787
RYDER: That one?
CHEVIE: Yeah.

34:17.790 --> 34:19.122
Let's see if
this chainsaw starts.

34:19.124 --> 34:20.857
I haven't started it in a while.

34:20.926 --> 34:22.059
RYDER: Can I try?
CHEVIE: Yeah.

34:25.130 --> 34:27.330
RYDER: You just pull it?
CHEVIE: Yeah, rip on it.

34:28.333 --> 34:29.850
(chainsaw rumbling)

34:29.902 --> 34:32.535
It's nice to be out
with my boy, you know?

34:32.538 --> 34:36.073
And, and to have that
father-son relationship.

34:36.141 --> 34:37.474
Sometimes I can be hard on him.

34:37.476 --> 34:39.742
Sometimes it's not
all fun and games.

34:39.745 --> 34:43.246
You know, so I wanna make
sure that I create times that are fun,

34:43.282 --> 34:46.349
that we get to have,
where it's just one-on-one.

34:46.418 --> 34:51.288
Um, and, and I can help him
learn a few different skills and

34:51.356 --> 34:54.224
he can enjoy those times,
and I can enjoy those times.

34:56.228 --> 34:57.561
On the shoulder?

34:57.629 --> 34:59.095
There you go.

34:59.098 --> 35:01.631
Thatta boy. Thatta boy.

35:02.634 --> 35:03.900
This is gonna be
a nice little load.

35:03.902 --> 35:06.636
This will get us smoking
fish for four or five days.

35:06.705 --> 35:08.171
I thought we were
gonna get a bunch of rain,

35:08.173 --> 35:10.574
get all wet, but it
actually turned out to be

35:10.642 --> 35:12.976
a really nice
evening for doing this.

35:16.047 --> 35:18.982
JOHNNY: When you're hunting
for food and not for sport,

35:18.984 --> 35:21.518
it's a very different feeling.

35:21.586 --> 35:23.854
Kind of primal instinct
just takes over me.

35:23.922 --> 35:29.993
And I feel like this hunter-gatherer
that's been shot into the future.

35:30.061 --> 35:33.930
It kind of parallels the way that
people lived for thousands of years.

35:37.936 --> 35:40.403
JOHNNY: This is caribou
droppings right here.

35:42.608 --> 35:46.543
And there's actually just a
little bit of snow around it.

35:46.545 --> 35:50.547
'Cause I keep getting this
kind of like on and off snow.

35:50.615 --> 35:52.215
Sleet.

35:52.217 --> 35:54.217
Where it melts in
the middle of the day.

35:54.286 --> 35:59.256
They're in the area but, uh,
exactly where is the question.

36:05.097 --> 36:07.063
Java, come on.

36:12.837 --> 36:15.238
Caribou swam across the lake.

36:15.307 --> 36:18.441
So, I'm hoping to kind of
come around and intercept them.

36:18.510 --> 36:20.710
And if the timing's right,
I'm thinking they'll be

36:20.779 --> 36:22.979
somewhere over in
this end of the lake.

36:25.250 --> 36:26.716
Time's ticking, man.

36:29.855 --> 36:31.388
Java, nice and easy girl.

36:31.456 --> 36:32.989
Hey.

36:38.847 --> 36:40.897
I thought I heard...

36:46.137 --> 36:47.771
Everything sounds
like an animal.

36:49.474 --> 36:50.707
Come on.

37:06.891 --> 37:08.892
I got a caribou.

37:08.960 --> 37:10.293
I got caribou right here.

37:12.764 --> 37:13.429
That's a big bull.

37:13.432 --> 37:14.798
(sighs)

37:25.043 --> 37:26.676
He see, he sees me.

37:36.988 --> 37:38.622
(gunshot)

37:44.863 --> 37:45.729
(gunshot)

37:45.797 --> 37:46.930
(bleep).

37:56.608 --> 37:57.707
(gunshot)

38:06.368 --> 38:07.834
(gunshot)

38:10.172 --> 38:11.671
JOHNNY: He's down.

38:17.579 --> 38:20.580
One caribou's not gonna
carry me through the winter.

38:20.649 --> 38:22.849
I need two,
I need three caribou.

38:22.851 --> 38:25.585
And that little herd
that was here I shot at,

38:25.587 --> 38:28.254
they just went around the
corner and they're still there.

38:28.323 --> 38:29.589
So I'm gonna try to
get another shot at them,

38:29.591 --> 38:31.057
get another caribou down.

38:43.005 --> 38:44.337
(gunshot)

38:46.741 --> 38:48.008
Go down, buddy.

38:50.478 --> 38:52.545
(dog whines)

38:53.682 --> 38:55.048
We got down a caribou.

38:58.286 --> 38:59.185
(sighs)

39:00.955 --> 39:01.821
That's it right there.

39:01.890 --> 39:03.089
That's two caribou.

39:03.158 --> 39:05.158
We got bull caribous.

39:05.226 --> 39:08.695
A little bit bigger than the
cow, so it's a little bit more meat.

39:08.697 --> 39:11.230
So two of 'em is gonna get
me a pretty good distance into

39:11.233 --> 39:13.966
the start of winter.

39:13.969 --> 39:17.237
You know, one caribou will
last me about six weeks,

39:17.305 --> 39:20.506
so having two of 'em is
a pretty good head start.

39:20.509 --> 39:22.842
I don't know if I'm gonna
see these animals again.

39:22.844 --> 39:25.044
It could be months
before I see 'em again,

39:25.047 --> 39:27.781
so it's, it's important
to get more than one.

39:27.849 --> 39:31.984
And that's the only way I can guarantee
myself meat and food this winter.

39:31.987 --> 39:35.855
And it's just, it's a tough,
tough place to live without meat.

39:35.924 --> 39:37.924
It, it's just you can't do it,

39:37.926 --> 39:41.261
and I've been
eating rice and beans,

39:41.329 --> 39:43.396
and it's just,
it's not sustainable, it's,

39:43.465 --> 39:45.632
I'm just hungry
all the time and,

39:48.069 --> 39:51.071
I got a lot of work to do, Java.

39:51.139 --> 39:52.138
You're excited though.

39:52.207 --> 39:53.540
You couldn't
even keep your cool.

39:57.011 --> 39:59.345
I just never know what's gonna
happen and every day I walk outside

39:59.347 --> 40:03.116
things change and you
just gotta be open to change.

40:05.020 --> 40:06.486
And I like the
challenges of that.

40:06.554 --> 40:08.821
I like the
challenges of, of adapting.

40:08.824 --> 40:13.493
I like not knowing what the
hell's gonna happen out here.

40:13.561 --> 40:16.563
That's essentially
how I live every day.

40:18.299 --> 40:20.300
When the
bounty's good, you take it.

40:20.368 --> 40:22.368
When it rains, you
put your buckets out.

40:22.437 --> 40:26.572
But, at the same time, I'm
also realizing that I've got

40:26.575 --> 40:29.476
a lot more work ahead of
me before that sun goes down.

40:31.913 --> 40:34.981
Just love all the
life happening out here.

40:34.983 --> 40:36.716
Sometimes with life comes death.

40:46.594 --> 40:48.995
WOMAN: Oh, Robert.
ROBERT: Look what we got for ya.

40:49.063 --> 40:53.733
WOMAN: Oh, my.
That is beautiful.

40:53.802 --> 40:56.269
That is really
gonna help me out.

40:56.271 --> 40:58.070
(speaking in native language)

40:58.073 --> 41:00.339
ROBERT: Thank you.
WOMAN: Welcome to come over.

41:00.342 --> 41:01.608
(speaking in native language)

41:01.676 --> 41:02.609
ROBERT: Oh, thank you.

41:02.677 --> 41:04.477
(speaking in native language)

41:04.546 --> 41:06.879
WOMAN: Robert, for all you do.

41:06.882 --> 41:10.216
It really helps out us elders.

41:10.285 --> 41:13.419
And I'm so glad that
you're continuing, both of you.

41:13.421 --> 41:15.221
Both of you.

41:15.223 --> 41:18.358
Because that's what's
gonna keep us going.

41:18.426 --> 41:19.692
ROBERT: Yeah.

41:19.694 --> 41:22.962
WOMAN: Is our younger
generation doing what we used to do.

41:22.964 --> 41:26.299
And I appreciate it so much.

41:26.301 --> 41:28.301
(speaking in native language)

41:28.369 --> 41:30.703
ROBERT: Giving this
meat to the elders,

41:30.772 --> 41:32.572
my son's following
in my footsteps.

41:32.640 --> 41:35.975
I'm so proud and so happy that
he gets to live that same lifestyle.

41:36.044 --> 41:38.711
'Cause it's brought me so
much happiness in my life.

41:38.780 --> 41:40.913
And I know it'll
do the same for him.

41:40.916 --> 41:45.585
I see him with the love
and passion for this land.

41:45.587 --> 41:47.320
That is priceless.

41:47.322 --> 41:48.388
This was a great day.

41:52.994 --> 41:53.726
SONTA: Good job.

41:53.728 --> 41:54.661
You guys did really good today.

41:54.729 --> 41:56.395
I'm proud of you guys
for working so hard and

41:56.398 --> 41:57.597
getting fish put up.

41:57.599 --> 41:59.398
You guys definitely learned
some skills this year and

41:59.401 --> 42:02.401
built on what you learned
last year and the year before.

42:02.404 --> 42:04.604
Ultimately, our kids
will know who they are.

42:04.672 --> 42:07.406
They'll know their
relationship to the land and

42:07.409 --> 42:10.810
they'll have a much stronger
bond to the place here.

42:10.812 --> 42:14.013
I think about it in terms
of generational knowledge.

42:14.015 --> 42:17.150
I wanna be that continuing
thread to the next generation,

42:17.218 --> 42:20.953
so that our kids
learn how to live this way.

42:20.956 --> 42:23.022
CHEVIE: This year is just
definitely a different year with the fish

42:23.091 --> 42:28.628
and the timing and, but we're still just
doing what we can do to fish this year.

42:28.630 --> 42:30.430
SONTA: It's always a nice thing
to have a little bit of fish

42:30.498 --> 42:33.165
put away for the winter and...

42:33.168 --> 42:34.500
One less thing to worry about.

42:34.569 --> 42:36.502
CHEVIE: Yup,
everybody did really good.

42:36.571 --> 42:38.972
SONTA: Everybody
did really good.

42:39.040 --> 42:41.174
CHEVIE: And those eggs
are gonna be delicious.

42:41.976 --> 42:44.210
EMERY: How dare you steal it.

42:51.453 --> 42:52.385
JOHNNY: It's hungry country.

42:52.387 --> 42:55.455
You know, everybody
out here's hungry.

42:55.523 --> 42:57.423
And today I'm not.

42:59.060 --> 43:00.727
It's a good feeling.

43:02.864 --> 43:07.333
It feels good to just kinda
stop a little bit in order to

43:07.335 --> 43:08.801
reflect on that hunt.

43:08.803 --> 43:12.672
Think about the animal's
lives and what that means to me,

43:12.674 --> 43:14.240
the gratitude.

43:18.280 --> 43:20.079
This is what hard work
tastes like right there.

43:20.415 --> 43:22.882
Alaska's the playing field.

43:22.951 --> 43:26.319
And what you choose to do with
Alaska is entirely up to you.

43:27.822 --> 43:30.890
You know,
hardships, pain, suffering,

43:30.892 --> 43:33.092
all that eventually goes away.

43:34.162 --> 43:36.696
But what you're forever left
with is the experiences and

43:36.698 --> 43:37.897
the lessons learned.

43:43.038 --> 43:44.304
PAT: Oh my goodness sakes.

43:44.372 --> 43:46.505
ROBERT: Enjoy it.
PAT: Thank you, Robert.

43:46.508 --> 43:49.442
ROBERT: Thank you.
PAT: Thank you, RJ.

43:49.510 --> 43:50.977
RJ: Thanks Pat.

43:50.979 --> 43:53.045
JOHNNY: The hardest,
toughest moments in life.

43:53.048 --> 43:55.848
Typically become the most
memorable moments in life.

43:55.917 --> 43:57.583
Hell of a day.

43:57.652 --> 43:59.052
Come on.

43:59.120 --> 44:01.120
And it's magic.

44:03.191 --> 44:06.859
You know, that's what keeps
me, uh, coming back out here.

44:06.861 --> 44:08.861
That's what keeps me
continuing the hunt,

44:08.863 --> 44:10.129
continuing the search.

44:14.736 --> 44:15.935
Because at the end of the day,

44:16.004 --> 44:18.671
it's not me that's
in charge, it's nature.

